master.notes: There seems to be an issue with the original release date of this album. According to the liner notes and copyright information of the 2013 reissue by FiveDayWeekend (FDW7711-LP), the LP first came out in 1967 (Columbia CS 9501) instead of 1968 as was previously stated on Discogs.com. While the original stereo pressing of the album does not state an issue or copyright date, the 2013 reissue very clearly states "© 1967, 2013 Sony Music Entertainment / Originally released 1967". Recordings for the LP took place in New York City in April and May, 1967.The LP release date 1967 is independently corroborated by McLuhan's biographer Philip Marchand, in his book "Marshall McLuhan: The Medium and the Message", Toronto: Random House 1989, p. 193. Jeffrey T. Schnapp and Adam Michaels equally document mid-1967 as the LP's release date in their book "The Electric Information Age Book: McLuhan/Agel/Fiore and the Experimental Paperback", New York: Princeton Architectural Press 2012, p. 57.

master.notes: The Wonderful World of Julie London is an LP album by Julie London, released by Liberty Records under catalog number LRP-3324 as a monophonic recording and catalog number LST-7324 in stereo in November 1963. This was Julie London's final charting album, reaching #136 on the Billboard charts.A CD format version of this entire album is found in the compilation [url=http://www.discogs.com/Julie-London-The-End-Of-The-World-The-Wonderful-World-Of-Julie-London/master/605371]"The End Of The World / The Wonderful World Of Julie London"[/url].

master.notes: The Earl Bostic King LPs with issue numbers 500, 503, 515, 525, 529, 547, 571, 558, 583 exist in basically two totally different versions:a) the mono issueb) the stereo issueThey differ in musical content in as much as the tunes are the same, but the personal and sometimes even the instrumentation are very much different on the mono and stereo versions.Although both releases have the same cover, the music on the stereo LPs  was recorded much, sometimes years, later than the music on the mono Lps.Since these are entirely different recordings, they should  be put under a different Master release. The Master release of the stereo version is here: [m1041038]

master.notes: Bad Penny Blues is a 1956 blues instrumental by Humphrey Lyttelton with significant boogie woogie piano by Johnny Parker. Jim Bray on bass and Stan Greig on drums. The official producer was Denis Preston but it was the then rather unknown Joe Meek as engineer who gave the recording it's fresh sound. Lyttelton has later referred to the piano as somewhat distorted and the drum whiskers as over recorded. He has later stated that had he heard it before release, he would have rejected it but didn't as it reached the top 20 before he did. The piano intro of Lady Madonna by The Beatles resembles Bad Penny Blues very much.
